author: Vatsalya Sharma
text: Delhi has withstood several assaults from outsiders for years and made the people of the city tough enough to withstand everything. Migrants would invade, but then eventually become one with the city. No-city in the world is such a melting pot of civilizations. It has been India's capital for ages and has been the centre of power and heritage. No city in the world can offer you glimpses of 3rd-century Hindu-Buddhist architecture, 14th-century Mughal architecture and 19th-century British architecture at a single place, all so beautiful, all so majestic. Its a city of romance and power, of religion, peace and hard work. But this latest assault is by the citizens themselves and not by any foreigners. Delhi has endured long enough, but this latest one, I don't know. Delhi is the synonym for endurance.\nPlease don't judge Delhi by the current problems. Delhi will find a way, it always has, for the last 2000 years.

author: xtw zyz
text:
Why pollution in India/China is so hard to fix

1. We are still developing economy, which means we are going to have large and quick industrial development, which will bring pollution. This have happened in Europe, but they already gotten pass the point.

2. Too many population. If you look at pollution/carbon emission per capita, China and India both rank a lot lower than developed countries such as the US, but we have 4-5 times the population concentrated in a few metropolitan areas. This is also another problem that can't be fixed in the next 10 or even 100 years. 

3. Still too many population, but this time the population also causes problem when the government trying to enact some sort of law to control the pollution. Environmental laws are usually enacted in the expense of having to shut down factories, slowing down economic development---reduce carbon emission, but many people will lose their jobs and their livings or be greatly affected by it.

In conclusion, we are trying our best to fight the problem, BUT THE PROBLEM IS NOT GOING TOBE FIXED JUST BY SOME RANDOM KID BITCHING ABOUT IT IN THE COMMENT SECTION.

I'm not saying that the pollution is okay in China, because it's not, but it doesn't seem to be a matter of population density. The amount of diesel cars in the last decade have increased ten-fold in India. Crop burning is also adding to a lot of the pollution. The government should attempt to restrict the amount of traffic in India, as well as look into more green and safe solutions than diesel cars.
